posts.title: Argentina minister: "In every industry we deregulate, prices fall 30%"
posts.content:
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=8b4SFDdAY_A

I watched this video by one of Milei's ministers who is helping him deregulate.

Some highlights:

  1. To speed up the deregulation process, they ask "What functions should a libertarian government do?" and made a list. Then they ask every single government employee "What do you do?" and if they are doing something that's not on the list, they try to re-assign the employee, or fire him, or even fire the whole department. There is no point is optimizing a department if it shouldn't exist to begin with.

  2. They have fired 15% of the entire federal workforce so far.

  3. To get help from the public in a speedy manner, they asked experts in various fields (who want de-regulation) to re-write the laws and submit new law texts to them. This weeds out input from all people who are unwilling to do work upfront to contribute. They then discuss the new law idea with the expert, and pass it into law if appropriate.

  4. In a few major industries they heavily deregulated, prices went down about 30% in each one. He gave the example of rent costs going down, and iron import costs, and some other things.

  5. The biggest obstacle is entrenched interests. These are unions, businesses who hire lobbyists, and bureaucracy employees. His advice for overcoming these: Work so fast to create new de-regulation law changes, that your opponents have no time to respond with their own counter-ideas. He says that their political opponents were stunned when Milei had a de-regulation law ready to pass in week 1 of his administration (because Milei had been planning how to de-regulate for 2 years ahead of time). Also, it helps a lot to have the President loudly praise a new de-regulation in the media. This builds hype for it, and makes it harder for lobbyists to convince politicians to oppose it. It's often the case that regulations only benefit a small number of rich businesses. When you point this out in the media, it becomes impossible for politicians to defend it to the voters.

  6. Milei's team are considering how to build sunset provisions into laws, to make laws expire automatically over time if they are no longer needed. He said one option is to tell a government agency: "Show me all the regulations you need to keep on the books. All other of your other regulations will automatically be deleted if you don't explain why you need to keep them." This can get rid of laws that were created by special interests many years ago, which don't benefit the public today.
